summary: Endgame spoilers - Loki and Tony
body:
Endgame spoilers - Loki and Tony

What I’ve really hated is the plot-hole created by the Tesseract and the easy way in which they could have solved it.

Instead of going back in the ‘70s, Tony could have just grabbed Loki’s ankle as he was teleporting away with the Tesseract and convinced him to hand it over (since Loki had experienced who Thanos was it’d have made sense to have him agree), and it would’ve been a lovely scene to see, with Tony and Loki interacting once again.

It would have also avoided the uncertainty regarding time travel and actions that can change the past, since after 2012 the Tesseract had remanained unused in Asgard.

And don’t get me started on the fact that Thor didn’t mention Loki even once

summary: this is gonna be so cheesy and sappy, but it’s from my heart and it’s true so here it is: regardless of what avengers: endgame...
body: this is gonna be so cheesy and sappy, but it’s from my heart and it’s true so here it is: regardless of what avengers: endgame contains and where his fate lies, i am just SO happy and proud of tony stark. i never thought i’d find another protagonist (whom i love so much) after katniss everdeen that resonated with me so personally, but tony has always been there. i grew up watching the first two Iron Man films and i loved them and i especially appreciate them now as an adult. to watch his journey and growth as a repressed playboy who finally found his purpose in life to a beloved superhero mentor who has gone through so many ups and down, whist growing up myself was such a rewarding experience that i wouldn’t trade for the world. it’s not often they show the repercussions of being a hero in the form of mental illness, so as somebody who struggles with anxiety it was so good to see a character go through the same thing and come out mostly ok in the end. tony’s only human and he made mistakes and his whole story has been him taking responsibility for your actions (whether it be direct or indirect) which is such a wonderful lesson to be taught in today’s world. his numerous relations onscreen has been an absolute pleasure to take in (romantic and amendable relationship with pepper, unbreakable friendship with rhodey, mentorship and psuedo father figure to peter, respectable dynamic with steve, found family within the avengers). even though i disagree with his politics, i’d like to thank robert downey jr. for his fantastic and iconic portrayal of tony, no one could’ve done it better. a big thank you to jon favreau for giving him to us, and to shane black, the russo bros and the writers for helping shape him. part of the journey is the end and however way his story ends, i’m going to cherish and love this character till the end. thank you so much for an amazing 10 years.
